influence subcontractors: The underlying chicken-and-egg problem 
Patrik Soderholm 
Luleå University of Technology, Economics Unit, SE-971 87, Luleå, Sweden   
ARTICLE INFO  
Keywords: 
Environmental permitting 
Regional development 
Mining operations 
Small- and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) 
Subcontractors 
Local employment ABSTRACT  
This paper addresses the link between the environmental permitting of mining operations and economic 
development in mineral-rich regions. The purpose is to investigate how uncertainty about the permitting out-
comes facing a mining company could affect its subcontractors. A key conceptual point of departure is that this 
influence can be related to both withheld investments and a lower demand for key inputs, including labor, but 
also to a reduced overall attractiveness of the community, in turn making it difficult to recruit skilled labor. These 
issues are illustrated in the empirical context of a Swedish iron ore producer, which for over two years faced the 
risk of having its existing environmental permit revoked. The results suggest that in this specific case, the main 
challenge for the affected subcontractors was increased difficulties in recruiting skilled personnel. At a general 
level, the findings indicate the need to devote increased research attention to the link between government 
regulation on the one hand, and business growth and regional development on the other, including reputational 
effects. The paper also discusses the implications for the reform of existing environmental permitting process, 
nevertheless arguing against the incorporation of additional dimensions of sustainability in this process.   
1.Introduction 
The mining and metals industry poses significant environmental 
impacts, such as large volumes of waste rock, tailings, acid mine 
drainage, nitrogen oxide emissions and airborne dust, but also emissions 
of sulfur dioxide and heavy metals in the smelting process of sulfide ores. 
For this reason, the mining operations, including processing plants and 
smelters, face increasingly stringent environmental regulations. While 
generally accepting the premise that regulations are needed, mining 
professionals worldwide have nevertheless raised concerns that 
permitting delays and uncertainties will lead to fewer investments (e.g., 
Cervantes et al., 2013 ). Existing permitting processes are often claimed 
to be unpredictable, non-transparent, and lacking in coordination across 
the responsible government authorities (e.g., Clagett, 2013 ; SNL Metals 
and Mining, 2015 ; Soderholm et al., 2015 ; Yıldız and Kural, 2020 ). This, 
it is argued, even constitutes a threat to sustainable development. For 
instance, the transition from a fossil fuel-based to a zero-carbon energy 
system hinges on the mining industry cost-effectively supplying a wide 
range of critical metals, which are required in the production of various 
sustainable energy technologies, e.g., wind turbines, solar PV modules, 
and electric batteries (Moreau et al., 2019 ). 
In this paper, we recognize that the presence of uncertain environmental permitting outcomes could not only affect the competi -
tiveness of the mining companies; any negative impacts could also 
create concern for the often-smaller firms that are subcontractors to a 
large mining venture. A subcontractor is a company who contracts with 
another company – the general contractor – to perform some of the latter 
company ’s work. Subcontractors allow the emergence of a vertical in-
dustrial cluster in which the allocation of labor is efficient (Segerstedt 
and Olofsson, 2010 ). In this way, subcontractors are often a vital 
component behind any general contractor ’s success. 
Nevertheless, when the general contractor experiences production 
disruptions and/or regulatory uncertainty, the subcontractors will also 
be affected. These spillover effects will be particularly profound when 
the subcontractors are small- and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), 
which are heavily reliant on the general contractor for its survival. This 
is sometimes the case in regions where one big mining company con-
stitutes a dominant part of the industrial structure in the regional 
economy (Andrews-Speed et al., 2005 ). Regulatory uncertainty can 
therefore influence not only the subcontractors as such, but also overall 
regional development. 
The purpose of the paper is to investigate how the uncertainty about 
environmental permitting outcomes facing a mining company could 
influence its subcontractors, not least SMEs. This is illustrated in the

2empirical context of the Swedish iron ore producer Kaunis Iron, which 
underwent an extended period (2018 –2022) of uncertainty regarding 
whether its existing environmental permit would be revoked or not (see 
the methods section for a brief introduction to the case), and its pri-
marily local subcontractors in the form of SMEs. The empirical analysis 
mainly rests on interviews with eight different subcontractors and two 
civil servants, the latter working with business development in the 
municipality hosting these iron ore extraction activities. 
Kitching (2006) makes the general remark that SMEs might change 
their behavior because of the behavior of other companies – such as 
significant contractors – adapting their behavior to regulatory change 
and/or uncertainties about future regulations. However, the “causal 
chains constituting the ‘invisible hand of regulation ’, connecting 
particular regulatory interventions to the actions of particular 
small-business owners, could […] be long and complex, ” (p. 801) (see 
also Kale and Arditi, 2001 ). In the paper, we present an analytical 
framework, which suggests that the regulatory uncertainty facing the 
mining industry could influence its subcontractors both through the 
demand side, i.e., withheld investments and a lower demand for key 
inputs, including labor, and the supply side, i.e., reduced overall 
attractiveness of the region, in turn making it more difficult to recruit 
skilled labor. These mechanisms are complements and not substitutes, 
and which of them that will dominate in practice remains an empirical 
question. 
By achieving the above, we contribute to existing research by con-
necting the environmental regulatory challenges to the process of eco-
nomic development in mining-dependent regions. Previous research has 
investigated the impact of environmental regulations on the competitive 
strength of the mining industry (e.g., Peck et al., 1992 ; Wilkerson, 2010 ; 
Annandale and Taplin, 2003 ; Tole and Koop, 2011 ), including how the 
environmental permitting processes can be designed and implemented 
without jeopardizing the competitiveness of industry (Soderholm et al., 
2015 , 2022 ; Campbell and Roberts, 2010 ; Lindmark och Bergquist, 
2008 ). A second strand of work investigates how the regional develop -
ment impacts of mining activities can be assessed empirically 
(Soderholm och Svahn, 2015 ; Clements and Johnson, 2000 ; Fleming and 
Measham, 2014 ; Rolfe et al., 2003 ; Moritz et al., 2017 ). This involves 
work on how mining closures could affect local communities (Marais, 
2013 ; Andrews-Speed et al., 2005 ), including what measures can be 
undertaken to mitigate any negative socio-economic effects (Syahrir 
et al., 2021 ). The present paper illustrates the relevance of merging these 
two strands in the literature by shedding new light on how merely the 
uncertainty about future environmental permitting outcomes could lead 
to negative spillover effects on subcontractors and overall regional 
development. 
In the next two sections we present the analytical framework and the 
methodological approach, respectively, while the remainder of the 
paper outlines and discusses the empirical findings that emerge from the 
interviews. Finally, a few generic implications from the analysis are 
discussed. 2.Analytical framework 
Fig. 1 summarizes the analytical framework of the paper. It recog -
nizes that the way in which subcontractors to a mining company will be 
affected by environmental regulation uncertainty facing the general 
contractor relates to the process of economic development in mining 
regions. An important point of departure for the framework is that this 
development involves a chicken-and-egg problem. Economic develop -
ment and regional employment growth can result from the establish -
ment and existence of mining operations; people will move to regions 
that host mining industries since these often offer high-paid jobs. This in- 
migration gives rise to several spillover effects on the regional economy 
(i.e., linkages). However, there is also the mechanism through which 
regions with several attractive features in terms of, e.g., housing, public 
services, and infrastructure, induces in-migration, and this in turn fa-
cilitates mining growth by securing future recruitments. In other words, 
people may move to regions that offer mining jobs, but jobs – and 
regional growth – will also be generated in regions where people wish to 
lead their lives. Fig. 1 outlines these mechanisms in more detail. 
First, by moving from left to right in Fig. 1, we can depict the variety 
of impacts that mining operations could have on regional development. 
These impacts can be both direct and indirect (Rolfe et al., 2003 ), where 
the direct impacts refer to the value added generated by the mining 
venture, and spent to compensate labour, capital, and any entrepre -
neurial efforts. The indirect impacts involve the linkages to other eco-
nomic activities in the region (e.g., Radetzki, 1982 ).1 The so-called 
backward linkages refer to the regional purchases of different required 
inputs. In brief, the prospects to produce capital goods, supplies and 
services needed for the investments and operations will be enhanced via 
the mineral operation ’s demand for such inputs. This will have a positive 
impact on subcontractors, and will also increase their purchases of factor 
inputs, including labor. The forward linkages refer to the various 
downstream activities, such as the processing, refining, and fabricating 
of the crude ores and concentrates. 
Both the direct and indirect impacts imply an increased demand for 
labor,2 and there is then prospects for in-migration to the region. The 
exact magnitude of this population increase will depend on several 
factors, such as the mining company ’s reliance on fly-in fly-out prac-
tices, and the degree of automation in the production process (Moritz 
et al., 2017 ). The resulting population increase will in turn give rise to 
additional linkages as the incomes of the new work force are spent on 
various goods and services in the region – so-called final-demand link-
ages. In addition, there are also fiscal linkages in the form of tax reve-
nues used by local governments to develop infrastructure and/or to 
purchase goods and services. The benefits of infrastructure investments 
and public services (e.g., roads, railways, electricity grids, schools, 
healthcare) will not solely be appropriated by the mining company, they 
will also spill over to other companies as well as to households (Eggert, 
2001 ). 
Second , by moving from right to left in Fig. 1, we can illustrate 
another – complementing – mechanism behind regional economic and 
employment growth. According to this perspective, in-migration, not 
least of highly educated persons, will be induced by the presence of 
attractive communities. Such communities are typically characterized 
by well-functioning and diverse housing markets (Mulder, 2006 ), access 
to high-quality transport infrastructure (e.g., railways, airports) (Buch 
et al., 2017 ), access to university education as well as high-quality 
Fig. 1.Mining and regional development: Two key mechanisms.  1 The linkage concept was introduced already by Hirschman (1958) and 
Watkins (1963) .  
2 The indirect impacts of mining operations are often expressed through so- 
called multipliers, which embody the effects of changes in demand for 
various goods and services (e.g., overall output) as well as inputs (e.g., labour) 
caused by the initial change in economic activity in mining (Fleming and 
Measham, 2014 ; Moritz et al., 2017 ). P. Soderholm

Resources Policy 82 (2023) 103585
3schools for the children (Zucker et al., 1998 ), but also more intangible 
features such as openness and tolerance in the community (e.g., Florida, 
2014 ). In other words, through this mechanism, housing, schools, and 
transport infrastructure are not primarily the consequences of industrial 
activity, but rather the prerequisites for in-migration and employment 
growth in the region. 
Research shows that access to key infrastructure such as airports and 
freeways will have direct positive impacts on economic growth; these 
attract investments and work opportunities in the region (e.g., Carbal -
lo-Cruz and Costa, 2014 ). However, the economic consequences also 
follow from the in-migration of a skilled workforce. This adds creativity 
and innovation potential to the region (Betz et al., 2016 ), in turn 
providing fertile ground for positive agglomeration effects in the form of 
more intense knowledge spillovers across related sectors in the regional 
economy. The level of technological development will in general be 
more profound in regions with high agglomeration compared to those 
with less agglomeration (Glaeser och Resseger, 2010 ). This will there -
fore benefit industrial activity and any associated subcontractors as 
there is increased scope for recruiting skilled workers as well as better 
prospects for technological development and innovation in the industry. 
The above implies that uncertainty about the future regulatory 
conditions for the mining sector could influence the economic situation 
for the industry ’s subcontractors in two main ways, viz.:  
≡through decreased investments and a lower demand for inputs, 
including labor. Any economic challenges facing the mining opera -
tion will spill over to the subcontractors in the form of weaker 
backward linkages and risks of staff layoffs; and 
≡anticipations of reduced industrial activity will diminish the pros-
pects for the future development of the community, including 
infrastructure and public services prompted by weaker fiscal link-
ages. This reduces the overall attractiveness of the region, thereby 
making it more difficult for the industry – including the sub-
contractors – to recruit skilled labor. 
Thus, the regulatory uncertainty facing the mining industry could 
influence its subcontractors through both the demand and the supply 
side. Clearly, the magnitudes of the above impacts will likely differ. For 
instance, the demand side impacts will in part depend on the extent to 
which the business activities in the region are built around the mining 
company (e.g., Andrews-Speed et al., 2005 ). Regions with a more 
diversified economy will be more effective in absorbing the regulatory 
uncertainty facing one of the mining companies in the region. Any 
negative supply-side impacts would likely also be less profound in a 
diversified economy, not least if the region is perceived overall attrac -
tive to potential in-migrating labor. 
3.Methods 
In this paper, we employ case study methodology as this permits a 
context-rich and explorative analysis (e.g., Flyvbjerg, 2006 ). Qualitative 
case studies typically offer deeper insights into the causal mechanisms 
through which various regulations influence the challenges facing 
business (Kitching, 2006 ). For our purposes, it is particularly important 
that case studies can help reveal how decisions tend to be made in sit-
uations of uncertainty, as well as mutual influence between the affected 
firms as well as between firms and regulators. In this paper, we aim at a 
simple empirical illustration, which can serve as an inspiration for more 
in-depth research in the future. 
Our case concerns the current iron ore mining operations of Kaunis 
Iron Inc. in the municipality of Pajala in northern Sweden. Fig. 2 is a map 
of the Nordic countries, indicating the location of these operations. The 
mining operations at this site have a relatively short history. In 2012, 
Northland Resources Inc., started an open pit to extract iron ore. How-
ever, the iron price fell heavily during the first two years, and in late 
2014 this company was declared bankrupt. This was a major shock for the municipality, including the subcontractors, which had experienced 
significant positive economic outcomes because of the new mine 
(Poelzer and Ejdemo, 2018 ). 
In 2018, Kaunis Iron acquired the assets in the Northland Resources 
bankruptcy estate, and a group of Swedish investors put up almost 600 
million SEK (around 53 million EUR). The new company could take over 
the old environmental permit and recommence the mining operations. 
However, just a few weeks before the restart of the ore extraction, the 
Swedish Environmental Protection Agency (SEPA) petitioned for Kaunis 
Iron’s environmental permit to be revoked. SEPA claimed that the op-
erations of the company were not in compliance with the conditions 
spelled out in the permit. This concerned the dimension of the water 
management system, and the fact that the ore from the mine was 
transported by trucks instead of by train. 
This gave rise to an uncertain period for Kaunis Iron and its sub-
contractors, and this ended in February 2022 when the Land and Envi-
ronmental Court of Appeal announced its decision, which stipulated that 
the existing permit was valid. In other words, SEPA ’s petition to revoke 
Kaunis Iron’s environmental permit was rejected and the mining com-
pany could continue its operations based on the existing permit. This 
verdict limits the annual production to seven million tons, which 
matches the current level of production. During this period (in July 
2019), the company also applied to the Land and Environmental Court 
for a new environmental permit embracing both the existing operations 
as well as two new mining operations in the region. This was not un-
important for the Court ’s decision concerning the existing permit, a 
decision which made it clear that revoking the permit would be 
unproportional given that a new permitting process had been initiated. 
Already in December 2022, the Court then announced its decision to 
grant Kaunis Iron the new permit. 
The empirical analysis builds on interviews and secondary data, the 
latter in the form of media coverage of the permitting process (e.g., 
Swedish Television, 2021 ). The interviews were all conducted during

Resources Policy 82 (2023) 103585
4the period June –August 2022. Specifically, we conducted ten 
semi-structured interviews, eight with business leaders of SMEs, all of 
them subcontractors to Kaunis Iron, and two with civil servants working 
at the municipality of Pajala. 
The eight subcontractors are all SMEs, and supply Kaunis Iron with 
several key inputs and services, incorporating machine contracting 
services, mechanical services, various operation and maintenance, in-
dustry components, protection gear, as well as explosives. All companies 
have been subcontractors to Kaunis Iron since the re-start of the mining 
operations in 2018, and many of them were also subcontractors to 
Northland Resources during the period 2012 –2014. It is essential to note 
that our sample consists of both small SMEs (two of them had less than 
ten employees), and larger ones (with one company having as many as 
170 employees). Moreover, the two civil servants worked with analyses 
of the business environment in Pajala, as well as with different strategies 
to promote business development at the local level. 
The interviews were conducted over telephone and lasted between 
32 and 51 min. The two guides for the interviews – one for the SME 
leaders and one for the civil servants – are outlined in brief in the Ap-
pendix. In general, we started all interviews by allowing the SME re-
spondents to speak openly about what they perceived the main 
consequences of the permitting uncertainty, and then reverted to more 
specific questions concerning the role of demand and supply side im-
pacts (in line with the analytical framework). 
4.Findings 
Following the establishment of first Northland and later Kaunis Iron, 
the municipality of Pajala in northern Sweden has become specialized in 
the mining industry. One of the civil servants at the municipal authority 
stated that Kaunis Iron has generated up to 1000 (direct and indirect) 
work opportunities in a municipality with around 6000 inhabitants. The 
representatives of the subcontractors confirmed that Kaunis Iron has 
been essential for their respective firms, a few even stating that in the 
absence of the mining operations, they would have had to shut down. 
Nevertheless, none of the respondents expressed that the uncertainty 
about the environmental permit of Kaunis Iron implied that they felt 
forced to lay off existing personnel. In fact, only two of them stated that 
they withheld investments and gave up existing plans to hire new staff. It 
is important to note that these two subcontractors are the two smallest 
SMEs in the sample, both with less than ten employees. The represen -
tatives of these companies also express that the businesses they have 
with Kaunis Iron were very vital for them, one even expressing that “we 
would not have an organization were it not for Kaunis Iron. ” In terms of 
negative linkages, one of the respondents noted: “we held our breaths 
and made no investments and did not hire new staff. ” Another expressed 
that one consequence of the uncertain situation was that the company 
withheld investments, in their case in new premises, and instead of 
hiring people full time, they tried to rent personnel and machines. 
One of the civil servants referred to how investments in hotel ac-
commodations were withdrawn, and the uncertainty about the future of 
the permit also negatively affected the possibility to obtain bank loans. 
None of the subcontractors, though, expressed that they had been 
negatively affected by a more restrictive credit market. 
The above thus suggests that the uncertainty about the future envi-
ronmental permit of Kaunis Iron resulted in weakened backward as well 
as final-demand linkages, but these impacts were not particularly pro-
found (except in the case of the small SMEs). There are likely two rea-
sons for this outcome. First, most of the subcontractors retained a 
positive attitude and commended Kaunis Iron for being transparent in its 
communication about the permit appeal process. For instance, one 
respondent noted that “if we had any questions regarding the uncertain 
situation, they [Kaunis Iron] answered, and we were therefore well- 
informed. ” For this reason, this same subcontractor also decided to 
continue their investments and “support Kaunis wholeheartedly. ” 
Another respondent noted that: “we have had very close contacts with Kaunis Iron and were updated about the situation, nobody in the com-
pany was really that worried. ” A few also noted that the mine had to be 
permitted since the socio-economic benefits were so significant. 
Second , some of the subcontractors approached – particularly the 
bigger companies – also had the opportunity to establish business in 
other municipalities with booming industrial activity, including various 
locations in Finland. One of the civil servants at Pajala municipality 
remarked that some of the bigger subcontractors “started to invest in the 
coastal region through subsidiary companies but they nevertheless fol-
lowed the situation in Pajala for any future investment opportunities ” in 
case the environmental permitting situation would be resolved. This was 
confirmed by the representatives of a few of the subcontractors, one 
noting that “when Kaunis Iron got the permit to continue production we 
nevertheless pursued our plans to expand business also in other parts of 
Sweden and in Finland. ” This firm was also a subcontractor to Northland 
Resources, and in a television interview one representative expressed 
that their current strategy to diversify their activities with investments 
also in other regions was in large part a lesson from the Northland 
experience (Swedish Television, 2021 ). 
As emphasized below, the biggest hurdle for these companies was 
not a lack of investment opportunities but rather a lack of skilled staff. 
For this reason, it was also deemed necessary not to lay off staff in Pajala 
since this would send a signal to both the existing staff and any potential 
new staff that the management of the company did not believe in 
continued iron ore extraction activities in the municipality of Pajala. 
One subcontractor noted that continued investments served “as signal to 
our employees that we were not worried about the future of Kaunis 
Iron. ” 
Thus, while there were some concerns about withheld investments 
and recruitments due to the uncertain permitting situation, the in-
terviews mainly confirmed that the most significant impact on sub-
contractors concerned the difficulties in hiring new personnel. Five of 
the respondents, representing both small and big SMEs, expressed this 
view.3 One of the smaller subcontractors emphasized the importance of 
recruiting the right people, and how recruitment became more difficult 
following SEPA ’s petition to revoke the environmental permit of Kaunis 
Iron: 
“We always try to identify the best personnel and are thus very se-
lective with respect to whom we hire. Pajala municipality does not 
have enough people to hire, and it was really a struggle to get people 
to work. We had a couple of people deny our offers due to the un-
certain situation in Pajala, so we were never able to reach full ca-
pacity. In the end, this had a negative effect on our production. ” 
Such recruiting difficulties were confirmed by the representatives of 
the other subcontractors approached. One of these noted that: “we had 
problems finding personnel due to the uncertain situation; people were 
skeptical about moving here and we often had to provide new staff with 
accommodation. ” As noted above, instead of hiring people full time, a 
few of the subcontractors (as well as Kaunis Iron) instead rented 
personnel, quite a few from Finland. 
The civil servants that were interviewed confirmed that the main 
challenge for SMEs in Pajala was to recruit new staff. Despite the un-
certain environmental permitting situation, which put some expansion 
plans at a hold, there existed all in all quite positive perceptions of the 
future business opportunities in the municipality. Some of the sub-
contractors to Kaunis Iron were keen to hire more staff, but potential 
employees did not share this positive assessment of the future. One of 
the civil servants at Pajala municipality noted: 
3 One respondent expressed that their firm was not affected much at all by the 
regulatory uncertainty facing Kaunis Iron, in part because of a weak depen -
dence on the mining company as a subcontractor. P. Soderholm

Resources Policy 82 (2023) 103585
5“Pajala has an aging population and need more younger people to 
move here. However, due to this uncertain permitting situation, 
people have been scared to move to the region. They had a hard time 
seeing themselves leading a life in Pajala. ” 
This disbelief did not only concern the future of Kaunis Iron as such, 
but the whole community, including the future of various public services 
(e.g., schools, healthcare), infrastructure and a well-functioning housing 
market. In fact, even though the mining operation continued throughout 
the period and earned profits, there was a decline in the population after 
SEPA ’s appeal to revoke the existing permit. Specifically, in 2018 when 
Kaunis Iron re-opened the mine, Pajala municipality had 6039 in-
habitants while the corresponding population in 2022 was 5883. One of 
the civil servants noted: “Work existed but people still quit and left.” 
Furthermore, it was also “hard for the local municipal administration to 
make any investments [e.g., in housing, infrastructure, public services] 
during this period of vacuum. ” 
The decision of the Land and Environmental Court in December 2022 
to grant Kaunis Iron an entirely new environmental permit, including 
the possibility to expand production, implies of course a much more 
stable investment environment. There is clearly a demand for the ser-
vices that subcontractors and their staff can offer. Nevertheless, it re-
mains to be seen whether this is enough to make people from other parts 
of the country – and not least, younger people – move to Pajala. Skilled 
labor does not only care about the future of potential employers, but also 
about the overall attractiveness of the region in terms of public services, 
infrastructure, housing supply and attitudes (see also Vaara et al., 2020 ). 
If such characteristics are lacking, families will find it hard to picture 
their future in a new region despite the presence of high-paid jobs. 
Moreover, one of the civil servants remarked that “companies will be 
more attractive for both investors and younger people if they are 
perceived sustainable, not least from an environmental perspective. ” For 
this reason, environmental permitting problems could send signals to 
potential employees that a mining company, which is facing the risk of 
losing its permit, is unable to live up to high environmental standards. 
Such negative perceptions of the mining company could of course affect 
the economics of subcontractors, and perhaps the way in which em-
ployees and other stakeholders also perceive their performance from a 
sustainability perspective. 
5.Concluding discussion 
The purpose of this paper was to examine how uncertainty about the 
environmental permitting outcomes confronting a mining company 
could influence its subcontractors and overall regional development. An 
important conceptual point of departure was that this influence can be 
related to withheld investments and stalled demand for key inputs, 
including labor, but also to a reduced overall attractiveness of the re-
gion, making it difficult to recruit skilled labor. This involves an un-
derlying chicken-and-egg problem: to what extent is the attractiveness 
of a region – e.g., the presence of high-quality public services and 
infrastructure – a consequence of, for instance, the fiscal linkages 
emanating from industrial activities, or instead an essential prerequisite 
for such activities since it stimulates the in-migration of skilled labor? 
Our results displayed that in the case of the environmental permit -
ting uncertainty facing Kaunis Iron, the main challenge for the affected 
subcontractors was increased difficulties in recruiting new skilled 
personnel. While withheld investments and halted recruitment pro-
cesses were also outcomes of the regulatory uncertainty, these negative 
impacts were nevertheless less profound. There are two explanations for 
this. First, the mining company maintained a close and trustful dialogue 
with its subcontractors. This is consistent with how Proctor (1996) de-
fines a healthy relationship between a general contractor and its sub-
contractors, noting not least the importance of consideration and 
communication. Second, some of the (bigger) subcontractors of Kaunis 
Iron had alternative investment opportunities in other parts of the wider regional area (northern Sweden and Finland), in part reflecting the 
importance of a diversified economy during periods of uncertainty and 
fears of mining closures (Andrews-Speed et al., 2005 ). 
Two important implications follow from the analysis in this paper. 
The first of these relates to the fact that both staff recruitment challenges 
and environmental permitting problems have been identified as key 
obstacles in the transition to a zero-carbon industry and energy system. 
This is evident in Sweden (e.g., Fossilfritt Sverige, 2019), but also in 
broader policy initiatives such as the U.S. Inflation Reduction Act and 
the European Union ’s so-called RepowerEU plan. Staff recruitment and 
environmental permitting are, however, typically perceived as isolated 
issues and are also therefore analyzed separately. This paper has shown 
that they are interconnected. The case of Kaunis Iron is an empirical 
illustration of this, and the conclusion likely applies to the entire green 
industrial transition currently taking place, including that in northern 
Sweden. 
Fig. 3 displays the results from a regular survey of the perceived 
growth barriers of SMEs in the county of Norrbotten – the northernmost 
county in Sweden and the host of Kaunis Iron’s operations. This survey 
has been conducted by the Swedish Growth Agency every third year 
since 2008, and Fig. 3 shows the percentage share of SMEs expressing 
that existing government regulations and access to skilled personnel, 
respectively, are significant barriers to business growth. 
Fig. 3 shows a close relationship between these two barriers to small 
business growth in the county of Norrbotten, Sweden. While this cannot 
be interpreted as proof of causality (merely correlation), it is interesting 
that these data are consistent with our case study results suggesting that 
government regulation hurdles can have negative impacts on staff 
recruitment prospects. This could provide one avenue for additional 
research on the relationship between government regulation on the one 
hand and SME growth and regional development on the other (see 
further below). As noted above, yet another link between regulation and 
regional development includes the reputational effects of mining com-
panies experiencing environmental permitting problems. 
A second implication of our findings in the paper is that SME growth 
and regional development constitute yet another reason to identify 
environmental permitting reforms that can help induce significant 
reduction in the environmental footprint of the mining industry without 
jeopardizing the competitiveness of industry and its subcontractors. One 
solution, which has been endorsed by the Swedish mining industry as-
sociation (e.g., Svemin, 2021 ; see also OECD, 2021 ), is the introduction 
of a more holistic permitting process, i.e., one which more clearly ac-
knowledges all three dimensions of sustainable development – ecolog -
ical, economic, and social sustainable development. In practice, this will 
imply that regional development issues, including the role of linkages in 
Fig. 3.The Perception of Barriers to Business Growth among SMEs in 
Norrbotten County (percentage share of respondents identifying each factor as 
a significant barrier) 
Source: Own construction based on survey data from the Swedish 
Growth Agency. P. Soderholm

Resources Policy 82 (2023) 103585
6the economy, would gain a more prominent place in the permitting 
decisions and be weighed against the importance of more stringent 
environmental requirements. 
However, this type of reform has clear drawbacks. First, overall, the 
key problem for industry in environmental permitting process is not so 
much stringent regulations on pollution, but rather uncertainty in terms 
of appeals and delays.4 Incorporating additional dimensions of sus-
tainable development into the permitting process risks increasing rather 
than decreasing this uncertainty. It would be difficult for industry to 
anticipate how various impacts would be weighed against each other in 
the permitting decisions, and there would likely be increased incentives 
among stakeholders to appeal such decisions. Second, the introduction 
of a more holistic environmental permitting process raises the question 
how the conditions in the permit should be expressed. For instance, if a 
mining operation is granted an environmental permit based on the 
premise that the regional employment impacts are significant (thus 
contributing to the social dimension of sustainable development), 
should this permit then be reassessed and potentially revoked if the 
owners of the operation afterwards invest in automation that reduces 
the direct employment? This could also add to the uncertainty facing the 
mining company. 
There are, though, other ways of reforming environmental permit -
ting processes. Soderholm et al. (2022) identify three aspects of an 
environmental permitting process that help minimize the risk of envi-
ronmental regulations counteracting industrial competitiveness. These 
include: (a) granting firms flexibility in identifying the most effective 
measures to comply with regulations and in terms of the time allowed 
for adjusting to new permitting conditions; (b) predictability with 
respect to the timeliness of the regulatory process, and transparency 
regarding how the legal rules will be interpreted in individual cases; and 
(c) high competence on the part of the regulatory authorities, providing 
scope for equal and trust-based consultations and knowledge-sharing 
between industry and government. Addressing the above will likely be 
more effective in avoiding future regulatory woes compared to a 
broadening of the scope of the permitting. 
Finally, this short paper has conceptually and empirically analyzed how regulation uncertainty could influence subcontractors and overall 
regional development. Clearly, however, our study mainly offers a 
simple empirical illustration, and there should be plenty of room for 
additional research. Environmental regulation uncertainty is a reoc-
curring issue, not least in connection to permit renewal following pro-
duction expansions, and therefore deserves to be studied in various 
empirical contexts, e.g., regions differing in terms of diversity and/or 
regulatory approaches. The reputational effects on the future recruiting 
of skilled personnel of permitting problems also deserve additional 
attention in future research, including whether such effects will differ 
depending on the design and implementation of the permitting process.
